#compdef rime_ls
# ============================================================================
# rime_ls - LSP server for Chinese / Japanese input via Rime (Rust, BSD-3-Clause)
#
# Author : Wang Linhan (wlh320)
# Upstream: https://github.com/wlh320/rime-ls
#
# rime_ls is a Language Server Protocol implementation that exposes
# the Rime input-method engine (`librime`) as LSP code-completion
# proposals: editors that speak LSP (Neovim, Emacs, VS Code,
# Helix, etc.) can input Chinese / Japanese / Korean / Vietnamese
# characters via the LSP completion-trigger pathway instead of
# the host OS's input method, which is useful when the editor is
# running over SSH / inside a remote container where no system-
# level IME is available.
#
# Operator modes:
#   rime_ls               - speak LSP over stdin/stdout (the default)
#   rime_ls --listen ADDR - speak LSP over TCP on the bind address
#                           (default 127.0.0.1:9257)
#
# The LSP lane is built on `tower-lsp = "0.20.0"` (declared verbatim
# at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD), the canonical async-Rust LSP server
# library by Eyal Kalderon (ebkalderon/tower-lsp, 1300+ stars).
# tower-lsp implements LSP 3.17 end-to-end: the JSON-RPC 2.0 codec
# layered on Microsoft's Base Protocol framing (Content-Length
# header + payload), the typed `LanguageServer` async trait
# covering 80+ request + notification methods (initialize / didOpen
# / didChange / completion / hover / definition / references /
# diagnostics / workspaceSymbol / codeAction / executeCommand /
# semantic tokens / call hierarchy / type hierarchy / inlay hints /
# etc.), and the tower service layer for middleware composition.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 216 :: LANGUAGE SERVER PROTOCOL (LSP 3.17, JSON-RPC 2.0)
# Round 1346 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 216
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis (proposed):
#   Rust    : ebkalderon/tower-lsp                          - async tower-based LSP server
#   Go      : tliron/glsp                                   - Go LSP server library
#   TS/Node : microsoft/vscode-languageserver-node          - reference + spec keeper
#
# The Node lane holds the reference implementation - Microsoft
# wrote LSP 3.x in 2016 and maintains both the spec and the
# TS/JS reference library, so every other lane's library is
# tested against `vscode-languageserver-node` for conformance.
# This is structurally similar to graphql-js (Axis 206), where
# the JS lane is canonical for the same reason: the spec text
# is derived from the JS reference implementation rather than
# the other way around.
#
# rime_ls is a non-traditional LSP server in that it returns
# input-method candidates rather than code-completion items -
# the LSP `completion` method is general enough to encompass
# both. This is the "creative use of LSP" pattern visible in
# other 2024-2026 servers like emoji-lsp, ai-completion-lsp,
# spell-check-lsp, etc.
# ============================================================================

_rime_ls() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--listen[run as a TCP LSP server (default 127.0.0.1:9257)]:bind address:' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]'
}

_rime_ls "$@"
